t, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sabran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Sabin  . This surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Sabin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Northamptonshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sabin</i> (from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>; see 2 below) or its female equivalent <i>Sabine</i> (from Latin <i>Sabina</i>). In medieval England the feminine form was always more popular as a personal name.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Sabin</i>, from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>. The name was originally referred to the Sabines, an ancient Italic people of central Italy whose name is of uncertain origin. In the 8th century  BC  the Romans slaughtered the Sabine menfolk and carried off the women. More influential as far as name-giving is concerned was the existence of several early Christian saints named <i>Sabinus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sabhán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sabh</i> ‘cub’. As an Irish surname, this has mostly been absorbed into   Savage  ."]}]},{"name":"Ermengarde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."],"variants":[{"name":"Irmengard","meanings":["Variant of   Ermengard ."]},{"name":"Irmingard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Ermgard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Irmgard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ermengarde De Sabran was born in 1170, in Mévouillon, Drôme, Rhône-Alpes, France. She married Prince Of Orange Guillaume Des Baux I on 21 March 1203. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1225, in France, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1170–1225":"1170–1225","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1185–1222":"1185–1222","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1192–1232":"1192–1232","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1202–1281":"1202–1281","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"umbes 1190","21 Mar 1203":"21. märts 1203","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1281":"1281","1170":"1170","1192":"1192","1239":"1239","1225":"1225","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1222":"1222","1232":"1232","about 1222":"umbes 1222","Puyricard, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Puyricard, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Prantsusmaa","Mévouillon, Drome, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Mévouillon, Drôme, Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Orange, Vaucluse, Provence, France":"Orange, Vaucluse, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1170–1225":"1170–1225","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1185–1222":"1185–1222","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1192–1232":"1192–1232","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1202–1281":"1202–1281","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"noin 1190","21 Mar 1203":"21. maaliskuuta 1203","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1281":"1281","1170":"1170","1192":"1192","1239":"1239","1225":"1225","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1222":"1222","1232":"1232","about 1222":"noin 1222","Puyricard, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Puyricard, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Ranska","Mévouillon, Drome, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Mévouillon, Drôme, Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Orange, Vaucluse, Provence, France":"Orange, Vaucluse, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1170–1225":"1170–1225","1174–Male":"1174–Décédé","1185–1222":"1185–1222","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1192–1232":"1192–1232","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1202–1281":"1202–1281","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"